          "body": "Verses 2-6 describe what the opened fountain implies: if sin is genuinely cleansed, the entire apparatus of counterfeit religion must go. The LORD of hosts declares three things He will remove — the names of the idols, the false prophets, and the unclean spirit (ruach tumah, 13:2). The triple purge is comprehensive: the objects of false worship, the human mediators of false religion, and the demonic source behind both. The names of idols will be cut off (karat) and no longer remembered — the same verb used for covenant-cutting and judicial execution. They will not merely be suppressed; they will be unmemorable. The treatment of false prophets in verses 3-6 is among the most arresting passages in the Minor Prophets. A prophet who still speaks falsely in the LORD's name will be executed by his own parents — the Mosaic law of Deuteronomy 13:6-10 and 18:20 re-invoked at full force. The false prophet, knowing this, renounces his identity: 'I am not a prophet; I am a tiller of the ground' (v. 5). But the wounds between his arms betray him — the self-laceration wounds of the false cult (cf. 1 Kings 18:28), which he tries to explain away as received 'in the house of my friends.' The hairy robe of verse 4 is not accidental costume; it deliberately mimics Elijah's garment (2 Kings 1:8), the recognized uniform of the true prophet. False prophets have always parasitized the appearance of true ones. In the day of the LORD, the impersonation becomes a liability — the very garment marks the wearer for shame."
